---
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button";
import { Leaf, History, TrendingUp, ArrowDown } from "lucide-react";
---

<!-- Slide 1: Research Intro -->
<section
    id="research-intro"
    data-chapter="research-intro"
    data-nav-label="Chapter 0: The Story"
    class="h-screen w-full flex items-center justify-center p-8 snap-start bg-muted/30 relative"
>
    <div class="container max-w-4xl text-center space-y-8">
        <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight lg:text-6xl text-gradient">
            Once Upon a Time, on Reddit
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
            They say the internet is a chaotic place. We say it’s a <span
                class="text-primary font-semibold">mirror</span
            >.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
            <span class="font-semibold text-foreground"
                >Welcome to our webpage!</span
            > We are the Data Appreciation Team, and we’ve spent months analyzing
            the Reddit Hyperlink Network, a massive web of connections between distinct
            communities. Our mission? Prove that online discourse isn't random; it
            follows the heartbeat of the physical world.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
            In the chapters ahead, you won't just see graphs. You will see the <span
                class="font-semibold text-foreground"
                >rhythm of the seasons</span
            > affecting our collective mood, watch <span
                class="font-semibold text-foreground">real-world history</span
            > get reconstructed by anomaly detection algorithms, and discover if a
            subreddit's anxiety can actually predict <span
                class="font-semibold text-foreground"
                >stock market
            </span> volatility.
        </p>

        <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
            This isn't just data analysis. It’s a map of the human experience,
            encoded in hyperlinks.
        </p>

        <div class="pt-8">
            <a href="#research-questions">
                <Button variant="outline" size="lg" className="gap-2">
                    Our Questions <ArrowDown className="h-4 w-4" />
                </Button>
            </a>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- Slide 2: Research Questions -->
<section
    id="research-questions"
    data-subchapter="research-questions"
    data-nav-label="Research Questions"
    class="min-h-screen w-full flex items-center justify-center p-8 snap-start bg-background relative overflow-hidden"
>
    <div class="container max-w-7xl flex flex-col gap-12 justify-center h-full">
        <div class="text-center space-y-6">
            <h3 class="text-3xl font-bold lg:text-5xl">
                Key Research Questions
            </h3>
            <p class="text-xl text-muted-foreground max-w-2xl mx-auto">
                To navigate a dataset of this magnitude, we needed a compass. We
                didn't just want to count links; we wanted to understand the
                human behavior driving them. We framed our investigation around
                three fundamental pillars, exploring how Time, Reality, and
                Value are encoded in our online interactions.
            </p>
        </div>

        {/* 3. TRANSITION & CARDS */}
        <div class="w-full space-y-8 max-w-5xl mx-auto">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 w-full text-left">
                {/* Card 1 - BLUE Theme */}
                <div
                    class="group p-6 rounded-2xl border border-border/60 bg-card transition-all duration-300 shadow-sm hover:shadow-md hover:border-blue-500/50 dark:hover:border-blue-400/50"
                >
                    <div
                        class="h-12 w-12 rounded-xl bg-blue-100 dark:bg-blue-900/20 text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 flex items-center justify-center mb-4 group-hover:scale-110 transition-transform duration-300"
                    >
                        <Leaf size={24} strokeWidth={2.5} />
                    </div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2 text-foreground">
                        The Rhythm of Seasons: "Do our digital emotions follow
                        the sun?"
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
                        We investigate whether the 'Winter Blues' or the 'Summer
                        Joy' are just myths or measurable phenomena. By tracking
                        specific emotional markers during time, we aim to
                        uncover the seasonal heartbeat hidden within millions of
                        comments.
                    </p>
                </div>

                {/* Card 2 - ORANGE Theme */}
                <div
                    class="group p-6 rounded-2xl border border-border/60 bg-card transition-all duration-300 shadow-sm hover:shadow-md hover:border-orange-500/50 dark:hover:border-orange-400/50"
                >
                    <div
                        class="h-12 w-12 rounded-xl bg-orange-100 dark:bg-orange-900/20 text-orange-600 dark:text-orange-400 flex items-center justify-center mb-4 group-hover:scale-110 transition-transform duration-300"
                    >
                        <History size={24} strokeWidth={2.5} />
                    </div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2 text-foreground">
                        The Echoes of Reality: "Can the crowd write history?"
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
                        When a major event shakes the real world, be it a
                        historic NBA game or a political election, does the
                        network react instantly? We use anomaly detection to
                        isolate massive spikes in activity, testing if we can
                        reconstruct the timeline of history purely from the
                        'noise' of community interactions.
                    </p>
                </div>

                {/* Card 3 - GREEN Theme */}
                <div
                    class="group p-6 rounded-2xl border border-border/60 bg-card transition-all duration-300 shadow-sm hover:shadow-md hover:border-green-500/50 dark:hover:border-green-400/50"
                >
                    <div
                        class="h-12 w-12 rounded-xl bg-green-100 dark:bg-green-900/20 text-green-600 dark:text-green-400 flex items-center justify-center mb-4 group-hover:scale-110 transition-transform duration-300"
                    >
                        <TrendingUp size={24} strokeWidth={2.5} />
                    </div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2 text-foreground">
                        The Financial Mirror: "Does volatility have a voice?"
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
                        Forget simple price prediction. We ask a more complex
                        question: Does the instability of our online sentiment
                        mirror the instability of the stock market? We analyze
                        the correlation between erratic subreddit behavior and
                        stock volatility to see if Wall Street dances to the
                        same emotional tune as Reddit.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex justify-center pt-8">
            <a href="#seasonal-intro">
                <Button size="lg" className="gap-2">
                    Start the Journey <ArrowDown className="h-4 w-4" />
                </Button>
            </a>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
